# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: topic-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In data mining and statistics, **hierarchical clustering** (also called **hierarchical cluster analysis** or **HCA**) is a method of cluster analysis that seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In general, the merges and splits are determined in a greedy manner.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The results of hierarchical clustering are usually presented in a dendrogram.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Hierarchical clustering has the distinct advantage that any valid measure of distance can be used.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In fact, the observations themselves are not required: all that is used is a matrix of distances.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] On the other hand, except for the special case of single-linkage distance, none of the algorithms (except exhaustive search in ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ ) can be guaranteed to find the optimum solution.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The standard algorithm for **hierarchical agglomerative clustering** (HAC) has a time complexity of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ and requires $\Omega (n^{2})$ memory, which makes it too slow for even medium data sets.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] However, for some special cases, optimal efficient agglomerative methods (of complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known: **SLINK** for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] With a heap, the runtime of the general case can be reduced to ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ , at the cost of additional the memory requirements.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In many cases, the memory overheads of this approach are too large to make it practically usable.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Methods exist which use quadtrees that demonstrate ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ total running time with ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ space.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Divisive clustering with an exhaustive search is ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ , but it is common to use faster heuristics to choose splits, such as *k*-means.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] While the linkage criterion determines how dissimilarity between sets of observations is computed, the underlying distance metric determines how dissimilarity between individual observations is measured.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering permits any valid measure of distance, the choice of metric is guided by the nature of the data and can have a significant effect on the resulting clustering.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] It is often preferred when features are measured on different scales or when the data contain outliers, as it is less sensitive to large deviations than Euclidean distance.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because it disregards vector magnitude, it is frequently used in text mining and document clustering, where documents are represented as high-dimensional term-frequency vectors.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike Euclidean distance, it is scale-invariant and is useful when features are correlated or measured in different units.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric interacts with the choice of linkage criterion.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] For example, Ward's method and centroid-based linkages are defined in terms of squared Euclidean distances, whereas single-linkage and complete-linkage clustering can be used with any valid metric.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In order to decide which clusters should be combined (for agglomerative), or where a cluster should be split (for divisive), a measure of dissimilarity between sets of observations is required.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric as well as linkage can have a major impact on the result of the clustering, where the lower level metric determines which objects are most similar, whereas the linkage criterion influences the shape of the clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] For example, complete-linkage tends to produce more spherical clusters than single-linkage.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The linkage criterion determines the distance between sets of observations as a function of the pairwise distances between observations.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Some of these can only be recomputed recursively (WPGMA, WPGMC), for many a recursive computation with Lance-Williams-equations is more efficient, while for other (Hausdorff, Medoid) the distances have to be computed with the slower full formula.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of linkage criterion significantly affects the shape and quality of the resulting clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Each method has distinct strengths and weaknesses depending on the structure of the data.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The naive implementation of agglomerative hierarchical clustering has a time complexity of O(*n*³) and a space complexity of O(*n*²), where *n* is the number of data points, because at each of the *n* − 1 merge steps the algorithm must search and update an *n* × *n* proximity matrix.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] For single linkage, optimized algorithms based on minimum spanning trees reduce the time complexity to O(*n*² log *n*).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] For other linkage criteria, the use of priority queues and nearest-neighbor chains can also achieve O(*n*² log *n*) time in practice.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Hausdorff linkage is a hierarchical clustering criterion based on the Hausdorff distance, a metric defined between sets of points in a given metric space.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike standard linkage methods that rely on pairwise distances between individual observations, Hausdorff linkage evaluates distances between entire clusters, thereby incorporating information about their geometric structure.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Formally, let $(S,\delta )$ be a metric space, and let A and B be nonempty compact subsets of S .
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This definition captures the largest distance from a point in one set to the closest point in the other set.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Equivalently, it can be interpreted as the smallest radius r such that every point of A lies within distance r of some point in B , and every point of B lies within distance r of some point in A .
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In this sense, the Hausdorff distance measures the maximum mismatch between two sets.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, Hausdorff linkage uses $d_{H}(A,B)$ as the dissimilarity measure between clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, each data point forms its own cluster, and the Hausdorff distance between singleton sets reduces to the original metric.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest Hausdorff distance are merged, and distances are recomputed using the same set-based definition.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This iterative process continues until all points belong to a single cluster, producing a hierarchical structure (dendrogram).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Compared to other linkage criteria such as single, complete, or average linkage, Hausdorff linkage operates on a set-to-set basis rather than relying solely on pairwise point distances.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] As a result, it captures the global geometry of clusters and can better preserve structural features of the data.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] It has been shown to provide behavior intermediate between single and complete linkage, avoiding the chaining effect of the former while reducing the tendency of the latter to overestimate distances between clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] However, these advantages come with increased computational cost.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Computing the Hausdorff distance between two clusters typically requires evaluating distances between all pairs of points across the sets, often via a max–min procedure over a distance matrix.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This makes Hausdorff linkage more computationally expensive than simpler linkage criteria, particularly for large datasets.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Overall, Hausdorff linkage provides a mathematically well-founded clustering approach that is effective for distinguishing complex structures in data.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] For example, suppose this data is to be clustered, and the Euclidean distance is the distance metric.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the tree at a given height will give a partitioning clustering at a selected precision.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In this example, cutting after the second row (from the top) of the dendrogram will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e} {f}.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting after the third row will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e f}, which is a coarser clustering, with a smaller number but larger clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The clustering process can also be illustrated step-by-step to show how the dendrogram is constructed from the underlying data.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In this visualization, each point begins as its own cluster.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest distance between them are merged.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] On the left, dashed lines indicate which clusters are combined, and a running list of cluster groupings shows how clusters evolve over time.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] On the right, the dendrogram is constructed simultaneously, with each merge represented by a new branch.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The height of each merge in the dendrogram corresponds to the distance or dissimilarity between the clusters being combined.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Merges that occur at lower heights represent clusters that are more similar, while merges at higher heights indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Color-coding is used to associate each merge step in the data visualization with its corresponding branch in the dendrogram.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] A key aspect of interpreting a dendrogram is understanding the meaning of branch height.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The height at which two clusters are joined represents the distance or dissimilarity between those clusters, where lower merges indicate greater similarity and higher merges indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Early merges at lower heights reflect the closest relationships between observations, while later merges combine increasingly different groups.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] When the dendrogram is scaled using actual or normalized distances, the vertical spacing between merges provides insight into the relative differences between clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Large vertical gaps between successive merges often indicate meaningful separations in the data.and can help guide the selection of cluster boundaries, although dendrograms alone should not be used to definitively determine the number of clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because dendrograms summarize underlying distance relationships, some information may be lost in the visualization, and interpretations are generally most reliable for clusters that merge at lower heights.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, the number of clusters is not determined automatically and must be chosen by analyzing the dendrogram.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] A common approach is to “cut” the dendrogram at a selected height, which partitions the data into clusters based on where the cut intersects the tree structure.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of cut level has a significant impact on the resulting clustering.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] One widely used heuristic is to identify large vertical gaps in the dendrogram, which correspond to substantial increases in the distance between successive merges.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the dendrogram at a height just before such a gap can produce clusters that reflect natural groupings in the data.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This is based on the observation that merges occurring at much larger distances often combine dissimilar clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In practice, the selection of the number of clusters may also depend on domain knowledge or application-specific requirements.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Quantitative measures such as the silhouette coefficient can be used to evaluate the quality of different clusterings.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering is sensitive to the choice of distance metric and linkage criterion, the optimal number of clusters may vary depending on these factors.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This method builds the hierarchy from the individual elements by progressively merging clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In our example, we have six elements {a} {b} {c} {d} {e} and {f}.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The first step is to determine which elements to merge in a cluster.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Usually, we want to take the two closest elements, according to the chosen distance.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Optionally, one can also construct a distance matrix at this stage, where the number in the *i*-th row *j*-th column is the distance between the *i*-th and *j*-th elements.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Then, as clustering progresses, rows and columns are merged as the clusters are merged and the distances updated.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This is a common way to implement this type of clustering, and has the benefit of caching distances between clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] A simple agglomerative clustering algorithm is described in the single-linkage clustering page; it can easily be adapted to different types of linkage (see below).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Suppose we have merged the two closest elements *b* and *c*, we now have the following clusters {*a*}, {*b*, *c*}, {*d*}, {*e*} and {*f*}, and want to merge them further.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] To do that, we need to take the distance between {a} and {b c}, and therefore define the distance between two clusters.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In case of tied minimum distances, a pair is randomly chosen, thus being able to generate several structurally different dendrograms.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Alternatively, all tied pairs may be joined at the same time, generating a unique dendrogram.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] One can always decide to stop clustering when there is a sufficiently small number of clusters (number criterion).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Some linkages may also guarantee that agglomeration occurs at a greater distance between clusters than the previous agglomeration, and then one can stop clustering when the clusters are too far apart to be merged (distance criterion).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] However, this is not the case of, e.g., the centroid linkage where the so-called reversals (inversions, departures from ultrametricity) may occur.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The basic principle of divisive clustering was published as the DIANA (DIvisive ANAlysis clustering) algorithm.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, all data is in the same cluster, and the largest cluster is split until every object is separate.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because there exist $O(2^{n})$ ways of splitting each cluster, heuristics are needed.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] DIANA chooses the object with the maximum average dissimilarity and then moves all objects to this cluster that are more similar to the new cluster than to the remainder.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Informally, DIANA is not so much a process of "dividing" as it is of "hollowing out": each iteration, an existing cluster (e.g. the initial cluster of the entire dataset) is chosen to form a new cluster inside of it.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Objects progressively move to this nested cluster, and hollow out the existing cluster.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Eventually, all that's left inside a cluster is nested clusters that grew there, without it owning any loose objects by itself.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] As long as $C_{*}$ isn't empty, keep migrating objects from $C_{*}$ to add them to $C_{\textrm {new}}$ .
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Intuitively, $D(i)$ above measures how strongly an object wants to leave its current cluster, but it is attenuated when the object wouldn't fit in the splinter group either.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Such objects will likely start their own splinter group eventually.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The dendrogram of DIANA can be constructed by letting the splinter group $C_{\textrm {new}}$ be a child of the hollowed-out cluster $C_{*}$ each time.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This constructs a tree with $C_{0}$ as its root and n unique single-object clusters as its leaves.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Standard hierarchical agglomerative clustering is difficult to apply to very large datasets because typical implementations require substantial memory for pairwise structures and can scale poorly as n grows (see § Complexity above).
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] In computational biology, single-cell technologies such as mass cytometry routinely produce tens of millions of high-dimensional observations, which motivates specialized workflows that preserve biological resolution without requiring that every expensive step be run on the full matrix at once.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The figure summarizes the HAL-x workflow: dimensionality reduction for density estimation, density-based seed clusters, a supervised linkage graph between clusters, and successive merges to a chosen generalization threshold.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] This design targets scalability: expensive steps are deliberately restricted to manageable downscaled subsamples, while label prediction can be applied broadly to the full dataset once the hierarchy and classifiers are established.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] Because of this, HAL-x is extremely useful when hierarchical clustering requires minimal RAM.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] A practical limitation, common to embedding-first pipelines, is that low-dimensional representations can distort global geometry and reduce accuracy.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The HAL-x paper discusses when auxiliary preprocessing such as PCA may help for correlated features.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] HAL-x was motivated by workflows in which biologists need many related clusterings at different granularities (for example to preserve rare leukocyte subsets while still summarizing abundant lineages) without repeatedly training separate models from scratch on millions of cells.
[src:topic-modeling/hierarchical-clustering] The authors report analyses on large cytometry-style datasets where rapid, tunable clusterings are used to support downstream interpretation of cellular phenotypes across conditions.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It is one of the most common topic models.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model was first presented as a graphical model for population genetics by J.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model was subsequently applied to machine learning by David Blei, Andrew Ng, and Michael I.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Although its most frequent application is in modeling text corpora, it has also been used for other problems, such as in clinical psychology, social science, and computational musicology.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The core assumption of LDA is that documents are represented as a random mixture of latent topics, and each topic is characterized by a probability distribution over words.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model is a generalization of probabilistic latent semantic analysis (pLSA), differing primarily in that LDA treats the topic mixture as a Dirichlet prior, leading to more reasonable mixtures and less susceptibility to overfitting.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Learning the latent topics and their associated probabilities from a corpus is typically done using Bayesian inference, often with methods like Gibbs sampling or variational Bayes.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the context of population genetics, LDA was proposed by J.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA was applied in machine learning by David Blei, Andrew Ng and Michael I.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In population genetics, the model is used to detect the presence of structured genetic variation in a group of individuals.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model assumes that alleles carried by individuals under study have origin in various extant or past populations.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model and various inference algorithms allow scientists to estimate the allele frequencies in those source populations and the origin of alleles carried by individuals under study.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The source populations can be interpreted ex-post in terms of various evolutionary scenarios.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In association studies, detecting the presence of genetic structure is considered a necessary preliminary step to avoid confounding.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In clinical psychology research, LDA has been used to identify common themes of self-images experienced by young people in social situations.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Other social scientists have used LDA to examine large sets of topical data from discussions on social media (e.g., tweets about prescription drugs).
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Additionally, **supervised Latent Dirichlet Allocation with covariates (SLDAX)** has been specifically developed to combine latent topics identified in texts with other manifest variables.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This approach allows for the integration of text data as predictors in statistical regression analyses, improving the accuracy of mental health predictions.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] One of the main advantages of SLDAX over traditional two-stage approaches is its ability to avoid biased estimates and incorrect standard errors, allowing for a more accurate analysis of psychological texts.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the field of social sciences, LDA has proven to be useful for analyzing large datasets, such as social media discussions.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For instance, researchers have used LDA to investigate tweets discussing socially relevant topics, like the use of prescription drugs and cultural differences in China.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] By analyzing these large text corpora, it is possible to uncover patterns and themes that might otherwise go unnoticed, offering valuable insights into public discourse and perception in real time.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the context of computational musicology, LDA has been used to discover tonal structures in different corpora.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A *topic* is considered to be a set of terms (i.e., individual words or phrases) that, taken together, suggest a shared theme.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] There may be many more topics in the collection – e.g., related to diet, grooming, healthcare, behavior, etc. that we do not discuss for simplicity's sake.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] (Very common, so called stop words in a language – e.g., "the", "an", "that", "are", "is", etc., – would not discriminate between topics and are usually filtered out by pre-processing before LDA is performed.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Certain terms are *ambiguous*, belonging to more than one topic, with different probability.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Most documents will contain only a relatively small number of topics.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the collection, e.g., individual topics will occur with differing frequencies.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] That is, they have a probability distribution, so that a given document is more likely to contain some topics than others.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Within a topic, certain terms will be used much more frequently than others.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In other words, the terms within a topic will also have their own probability distribution.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] When LDA machine learning is employed, both sets of probabilities are computed during the training phase, using Bayesian methods and an expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA is a generalization of older approach of probabilistic latent semantic analysis (pLSA), The pLSA model is equivalent to LDA under a uniform Dirichlet prior distribution. pLSA relies on only the first two assumptions above and does not care about the remainder.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] With plate notation, which is often used to represent probabilistic graphical models (PGMs), the dependencies among the many variables can be captured concisely.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The boxes are "plates" representing replicates, which are repeated entities.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The outer plate represents documents, while the inner plate represents the repeated word positions in a given document; each position is associated with a choice of topic and word.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The fact that W is grayed out means that words $w_{ij}$ are the only observable variables, and the other variables are latent variables.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] As proposed in the original paper, a sparse Dirichlet prior can be used to model the topic-word distribution, following the intuition that the probability distribution over words in a topic is skewed, so that only a small set of words have high probability.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The resulting model is the most widely applied variant of LDA today.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The plate notation for this model is shown on the right, where K denotes the number of topics and $\varphi _{1},\dots ,\varphi _{K}$ *are* V -dimensional vectors storing the parameters of the Dirichlet-distributed topic-word distributions ( V is the number of words in the vocabulary).
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It is helpful to think of the entities represented by $\theta$ and $\varphi$ as matrices created by decomposing the original document-word matrix that represents the corpus of documents being modeled.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In this view, $\theta$ consists of rows defined by documents and columns defined by topics, while $\varphi$ consists of rows defined by topics and columns defined by words.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Thus, $\varphi _{1},\dots ,\varphi _{K}$ refers to a set of rows, or vectors, each of which is a distribution over words, and $\theta _{1},\dots ,\theta _{M}$ refers to a set of rows, each of which is a distribution over topics.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] To actually infer the topics in a corpus, we imagine a generative process whereby the documents are created, so that we may infer, or reverse engineer, it.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] We imagine the generative process as follows.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Documents are represented as random mixtures over latent topics, where each topic is characterized by a distribution over all the words.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The lengths $N_{i}$ are treated as independent of all the other data generating variables ( w and z ).
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The subscript is often dropped, as in the plate diagrams shown here.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Learning the various distributions (the set of topics, their associated word probabilities, the topic of each word, and the particular topic mixture of each document) is a problem of statistical inference.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The original paper by Pritchard et al. used approximation of the posterior distribution by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Alternative proposal of inference techniques include Gibbs sampling.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The original ML paper used a variational Bayes approximation of the posterior distribution.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A direct optimization of the likelihood with a block relaxation algorithm proves to be a fast alternative to MCMC.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In practice, the optimal number of populations or topics is not known beforehand.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It can be estimated by approximation of the posterior distribution with reversible-jump Markov chain Monte Carlo.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Alternative approaches include expectation propagation.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Recent research has been focused on speeding up the inference of latent Dirichlet allocation to support the capture of a massive number of topics in a large number of documents.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The update equation of the collapsed Gibbs sampler mentioned in the earlier section has a natural sparsity within it that can be taken advantage of.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Intuitively, since each document only contains a subset of topics $K_{d}$ , and a word also only appears in a subset of topics $K_{w}$ , the above update equation could be rewritten to take advantage of this sparsity.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In this equation, we have three terms, out of which two are sparse, and the other is small.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] We call these terms $a,b$ and c respectively.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Here, we can see that B is a summation of the topics that appear in document d , and C is also a sparse summation of the topics that a word w is assigned to across the whole corpus.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A on the other hand, is dense but because of the small values of $\alpha$ & $\beta$ , the value is very small compared to the two other terms.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now, while sampling a topic, if we sample a random variable uniformly from $s\sim U(s|\mid A+B+C)$ , we can check which bucket our sample lands in.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Since A is small, we are very unlikely to fall into this bucket; however, if we do fall into this bucket, sampling a topic takes $O(K)$ time (same as the original Collapsed Gibbs Sampler).
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] However, if we fall into the other two buckets, we only need to check a subset of topics if we keep a record of the sparse topics.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A topic can be sampled from the B bucket in $O(K_{d})$ time, and a topic can be sampled from the C bucket in $O(K_{w})$ time where $K_{d}$ and $K_{w}$ denotes the number of topics assigned to the current document and current word type respectively.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Notice that after sampling each topic, updating these buckets is all basic $O(1)$ arithmetic operations.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Following is the derivation of the equations for collapsed Gibbs sampling, which means $\varphi$ s and $\theta$ s will be integrated out.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For simplicity, in this derivation the documents are all assumed to have the same length $N_{}$ .
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The derivation is equally valid if the document lengths vary.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] where the bold-font variables denote the vector version of the variables.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] First, ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ need to be integrated out.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] All the $\theta$ s are independent to each other and the same to all the $\varphi$ s.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] So we can treat each $\theta$ and each $\varphi$ separately.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Actually, it is the hidden part of the model for the $j^{th}$ document.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now we replace the probabilities in the above equation by the true distribution expression to write out the explicit equation.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Let $n_{j,r}^{i}$ be the number of word tokens in the $j^{th}$ document with the same word symbol (the $r^{th}$ word in the vocabulary) assigned to the $i^{th}$ topic.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] If any of the three dimensions is not limited to a specific value, we use a parenthesized point $(\cdot )$ to denote.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For example, $n_{j,(\cdot )}^{i}$ denotes the number of word tokens in the $j^{th}$ document assigned to the $i^{th}$ topic.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The equation inside the integration has the same form as the Dirichlet distribution.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now we turn our attention to the ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ part.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Actually, the derivation of the ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ part is very similar to the ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ part.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The goal of Gibbs Sampling here is to approximate the distribution of $P({\boldsymbol {Z}}\mid {\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ .
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Since $P({\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ is invariable for any of Z, Gibbs Sampling equations can be derived from $P({\boldsymbol {Z}},{\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ directly.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] where $Z_{(m,n)}$ denotes the Z hidden variable of the $n^{th}$ word token in the $m^{th}$ document.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] And further we assume that the word symbol of it is the $v^{th}$ word in the vocabulary, i.e. $W_{(m,n)}=v$ . ${\boldsymbol {Z_{-(m,n)}}}$ denotes all the Z s but $Z_{(m,n)}$ .
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] but the ratios among the probabilities that $Z_{(m,n)}$ can take value.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The above equation can be further simplified leveraging the property of gamma function.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Note that the same formula is derived in the article on the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution, as part of a more general discussion of integrating Dirichlet distribution priors out of a Bayesian network.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Topic modeling is a classic solution to the problem of information retrieval using linked data and semantic web technology.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Related models and techniques are, among others, latent semantic indexing, independent component analysis, probabilistic latent semantic indexing, non-negative matrix factorization, and Gamma-Poisson distribution.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model is highly modular and can therefore be easily extended.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The main field of interest is modeling relations between topics.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This is achieved by using another distribution on the simplex instead of the Dirichlet.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The Correlated Topic Model follows this approach, inducing a correlation structure between topics by using the logistic normal distribution instead of the Dirichlet.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Another extension is the hierarchical LDA (hLDA), where topics are joined together in a hierarchy by using the nested Chinese restaurant process, whose structure is learnt from data.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA can also be extended to a corpus in which a document includes two types of information (e.g., words and names), as in the LDA-dual model.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Nonparametric extensions of LDA include the hierarchical Dirichlet process mixture model, which allows the number of topics to be unbounded and learnt from data.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] As noted earlier, pLSA is similar to LDA.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model is essentially the Bayesian version of pLSA model.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The Bayesian formulation tends to perform better on small datasets because Bayesian methods can avoid overfitting the data.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For very large datasets, the results of the two models tend to converge.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] One difference is that pLSA uses a variable d to represent a document in the training set.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] So in pLSA, when presented with a document the model has not seen before, we fix $\Pr(w\mid z)$ —the probability of words under topics—to be that learned from the training set and use the same EM algorithm to infer $\Pr(z\mid d)$ —the topic distribution under d .
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Blei argues that this step is cheating because you are essentially refitting the model to the new data.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In evolutionary biology, it is often natural to assume that the geographic locations of the individuals observed bring some information about their ancestry.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This is the rational of various models for geo-referenced genetic data.
[src:topic-modeling/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Variations on LDA have been used to automatically put natural images into categories, such as "bedroom" or "forest", by treating an image as a document, and small patches of the image as words; one of the variations is called spatial latent Dirichlet allocation.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] In linguistics and natural language processing, a **corpus** (pl.: **corpora**) or **text corpus** is a dataset, consisting of natively digital and older, digitalized, language resources, either annotated or unannotated.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Annotated, they have been used in corpus linguistics for statistical hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] A corpus may contain texts in a single language (*monolingual corpus*) or text data in multiple languages (*multilingual corpus*).
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] In order to make the corpora more useful for doing linguistic research, they are often subjected to a process known as annotation.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] An example of annotating a corpus is part-of-speech tagging, or *POS-tagging*, in which information about each word's part of speech (verb, noun, adjective, etc.) is added to the corpus in the form of *tags*.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Another example is indicating the lemma (base) form of each word.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] When the language of the corpus is not a working language of the researchers who use it, interlinear glossing is used to make the annotation bilingual.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Some corpora have further *structured* levels of analysis applied.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] In particular, smaller corpora may be fully parsed.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Such corpora are usually called Treebanks or Parsed Corpora.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] The difficulty of ensuring that the entire corpus is completely and consistently annotated means that these corpora are usually smaller, containing around one to three million words.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Other levels of linguistic structured analysis are possible, including annotations for morphology, semantics and pragmatics.
[src:topic-modeling/text-corpus] Corpora are the main knowledge base in corpus linguistics.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In information retrieval, **tf–idf** (**term frequency–inverse document frequency**, **TF*IDF**, **TFIDF**, **TF–IDF**, or **Tf–idf**) is a measure of importance of a word to a document in a collection or corpus, adjusted for the fact that some words appear more frequently in general.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Like the bag-of-words model, it models a document as a multiset of words, without word order.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] It is a refinement over the simple bag-of-words model, by allowing the weight of words to depend on the rest of the corpus.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] It was often used as a weighting factor in searches of information retrieval, text mining, and user modeling.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] A survey conducted in 2015 showed that 83% of text-based recommender systems in digital libraries used tf–idf.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Variations of the tf–idf weighting scheme were often used by search engines as a central tool in scoring and ranking a document's relevance given a user query.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] One of the simplest ranking functions is computed by summing the tf–idf for each query term; many more sophisticated ranking functions are variants of this simple model.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] We see that "Romeo", "Falstaff", and "salad" appears in very few plays, so seeing these words, one could get a good idea as to which play it might be.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In contrast, "good" and "sweet" appears in every play and are completely uninformative as to which play it is.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] A formula that aims to define the importance of a keyword or phrase within a document or a web page.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] where *f**t*,*d* is the *raw count* of a term in a document, i.e., the number of times that term t occurs in document d.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Note the denominator is simply the total number of terms in document *d* (counting each occurrence of the same term separately).
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The **inverse document frequency** is a measure of how much information the word provides, i.e., how common or rare it is across all documents.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] A high weight in tf–idf is reached by a high term frequency (in the given document) and a low document frequency of the term in the whole collection of documents; the weights hence tend to filter out common terms.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Since the ratio inside the idf's log function is always greater than or equal to 1, the value of idf (and tf–idf) is greater than or equal to 0.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] As a term appears in more documents, the ratio inside the logarithm approaches 1, bringing the idf and tf–idf closer to 0.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Idf was introduced as "term specificity" by Karen Spärck Jones in a 1972 paper.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Although it has worked well as a heuristic, its theoretical foundations have been troublesome for at least three decades afterward, with many researchers trying to find information theoretic justifications for it.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Spärck Jones's own explanation did not propose much theory, aside from a connection to Zipf's law.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Namely, the inverse document frequency is the logarithm of "inverse" relative document frequency.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] This probabilistic interpretation in turn takes the same form as that of self-information.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] However, applying such information-theoretic notions to problems in information retrieval leads to problems when trying to define the appropriate event spaces for the required probability distributions: not only documents need to be taken into account, but also queries and terms.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Both term frequency and inverse document frequency can be formulated in terms of information theory; it helps to understand why their product has a meaning in terms of joint informational content of a document.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In terms of notation, ${\cal {D}}$ and ${\cal {T}}$ are "random variables" corresponding to respectively draw a document or a term.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] This expression shows that summing the Tf–idf of all possible terms and documents recovers the mutual information between documents and term taking into account all the specificities of their joint distribution.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Each Tf–idf hence carries the "bit of information" attached to a term x document pair.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Tf–idf is closely related to the negative logarithmically transformed *p*-value from a one-tailed formulation of Fisher's exact test when the underlying corpus documents satisfy certain idealized assumptions.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] More recently, tf–idf variants were shown to arise as components in the test statistic of a penalized likelihood-ratio test for word burstiness based on a beta-binomial statistical language model.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In this framework, the null hypothesis models term occurrences using a binomial distribution, while the alternative hypothesis models word burstiness using a beta-binomial distribution with a gamma-distributed penalty term placed on the beta-binomial precision parameter.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The resulting test statistic contains the tf–idf variants binary term frequency–inverse document frequency (btf–idf) and term frequency–inverse collection frequency (tf–icf), thereby establishing a direct connection between tf–idf family term-weighting schemes and statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In its raw frequency form, tf is just the frequency of the "this" for each document.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In each document, the word "this" appears once; but as the document 2 has more words, its relative frequency is smaller.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] An idf is constant per corpus, and **accounts** for the ratio of documents that include the word "this".
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In this case, we have a corpus of two documents and all of them include the word "this".
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] So tf–idf is zero for the word "this", which implies that the word is not very informative as it appears in all documents.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The idea behind tf–idf also applies to entities other than terms.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In 1998, the concept of idf was applied to citations.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The authors argued that "if a very uncommon citation is shared by two documents, this should be weighted more highly than a citation made by a large number of documents".
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In addition, tf–idf was applied to "visual words" with the purpose of conducting object matching in videos, and entire sentences.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] However, the concept of tf–idf did not prove to be more effective in all cases than a plain tf scheme (without idf).
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] When tf–idf was applied to citations, researchers could find no improvement over a simple citation-count weight that had no idf component.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] A number of term-weighting schemes have derived from tf–idf.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] One of them is TF–PDF (term frequency * proportional document frequency).
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] TF–PDF was introduced in 2001 in the context of identifying emerging topics in the media.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The PDF component measures the difference of how often a term occurs in different domains.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] In TF–IDuF, idf is not calculated based on the document corpus that is to be searched or recommended.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] Instead, idf is calculated on users' personal document collections.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The authors report that TF–IDuF was equally effective as tf–idf but could also be applied in situations when, e.g., a user modeling system has no access to a global document corpus.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] The DELTA TF-IDF derivative uses the difference in importance of a term across two specific classes, like positive and negative sentiment.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] For example, it can assign a high score to a word like "excellent" in positive reviews and a low score to the same word in negative reviews.
[src:topic-modeling/tf-idf] This helps identify words that strongly indicate the sentiment of a document, potentially leading to improved accuracy in text classification tasks.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In natural language processing, a **topic model** is a type of probabilistic, neural, or algebraic model for discovering the abstract topics that occur in a collection of documents.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Topic modeling is a frequently used text mining tool for discovering hidden semantic features and structures in a text.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] The topics produced by topic models are generated through a variety of mathematical frameworks, including probabilistic generative models, matrix factorization methods based on word co-occurrence, and clustering algorithms applied to semantic embeddings.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Topic models are commonly used to organize and discover latent features in large collections of unstructured text and other forms of big data.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Beyond text mining, topic models have also been used to uncover latent structures in fields such as genetic information, bioinformatics, computer vision, and social networks.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] An early topic model was described by Papadimitriou, Raghavan, Tamaki and Vempala in 1998.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Another one, called probabilistic latent semantic analysis (PLSA), was created by Thomas Hofmann in 1999.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), perhaps the most common topic model currently in use, is a generalization of PLSA.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Developed by David Blei, Andrew Ng, and Michael I.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Jordan in 2002, LDA introduces sparse Dirichlet prior distributions over document-topic and topic-word distributions, encoding the intuition that documents cover a small number of topics and that topics often use a small number of words.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Other topic models are generally extensions on LDA, such as Pachinko allocation, which improves on LDA by modeling correlations between topics in addition to the word correlations which constitute topics.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Hierarchical latent tree analysis (HLTA) is an alternative to LDA, which models word co-occurrence using a tree of latent variables and the states of the latent variables, which correspond to soft clusters of documents, are interpreted as topics.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Approaches for temporal information include Block and Newman's determination of the temporal dynamics of topics in the *Pennsylvania Gazette* during 1728–1800.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Griffiths & Steyvers used topic modeling on abstracts from the journal *PNAS* to identify topics that rose or fell in popularity from 1991 to 2001 whereas Lamba & Madhusushan used topic modeling on full-text research articles retrieved from DJLIT journal from 1981 to 2018.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In the field of library and information science, Lamba & Madhusudhan applied topic modeling on different Indian resources like journal articles and electronic theses and resources (ETDs).
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Nelson has been analyzing change in topics over time in the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* to understand social and political changes and continuities in Richmond during the American Civil War.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Yang, Torget and Mihalcea applied topic modeling methods to newspapers from 1829 to 2008.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Mimno used topic modelling with 24 journals on classical philology and archaeology spanning 150 years to look at how topics in the journals change over time and how the journals become more different or similar over time.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Yin et al. introduced a topic model for geographically distributed documents, where document positions are explained by latent regions which are detected during inference.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Chang and Blei included network information between linked documents in the relational topic model, to model the links between websites.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] The author-topic model by Rosen-Zvi et al. models the topics associated with authors of documents to improve the topic detection for documents with authorship information.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] HLTA was applied to a collection of recent research papers published at major AI and Machine Learning venues.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] The resulting model is called The AI Tree.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] The resulting topics are used to index the papers at aipano.cse.ust.hk to help researchers track research trends and identify papers to read, and help conference organizers and journal editors identify reviewers for submissions.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] To improve the qualitative aspects and coherency of generated topics, some researchers have explored the efficacy of "coherence scores", or otherwise how computer-extracted clusters (i.e. topics) align with a human benchmark.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Coherence scores are metrics for optimising the number of topics to extract from a document corpus.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In practice, researchers attempt to fit appropriate model parameters to the data corpus using one of several heuristics for maximum likelihood fit.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Blei describes this suite of algorithms.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Several groups of researchers starting with Papadimitriou et al. have attempted to design algorithms with provable guarantees.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Assuming that the data were actually generated by the model in question, they try to design algorithms that probably find the model that was used to create the data.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Techniques used here include singular value decomposition (SVD) and the method of moments.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In 2012 an algorithm based upon non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) was introduced that also generalizes to topic models with correlations among topics.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Since 2017, neural networks has been leveraged in topic modeling in order to improve the speed of inference, and leading to further advancements like vONTSS, which allows humans to incorporate domain knowledge via weakly supervised learning.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In 2018, a new approach to topic models was proposed based on the stochastic block model.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Topic modeling has leveraged LLMs through contextual embedding and fine tuning.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Topic models are also used in other contexts.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] For example, uses of topic models in biology and bioinformatics research have emerged.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Recently, topic models have been used to extract information from a dataset of genomic samples of cancers.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] In this case, topics are biological latent variables to be inferred.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] Topic models can be used for analysis of music.
[src:topic-modeling/topic-model] For instance, topic models were used to quantify how musical styles change in time, and identify the influence of specific artists on later music creation.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] In this section we consider a particular vector space model based on the bag-of-words representation.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Documents and queries are represented as vectors.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Each dimension corresponds to a separate term.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] If a term occurs in the document, its value in the vector is non-zero.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Several different ways of computing these values, also known as (term) weights, have been developed.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] One of the best known schemes is tf-idf weighting (see the example below).
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] The definition of *term* depends on the application.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Typically terms are single words, keywords, or longer phrases.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] If words are chosen to be the terms, the dimensionality of the vector is the number of words in the vocabulary (the number of distinct words occurring in the corpus).
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Vector operations can be used to compare documents with queries.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Candidate documents from the corpus can be retrieved and ranked using a variety of methods.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Where $\mathbf {d_{2}} \cdot \mathbf {q}$ is the intersection (i.e. the dot product) of the document (d2 in the figure to the right) and the query (q in the figure) vectors, $\left\|\mathbf {d_{2}} \right\|$ is the norm of vector d2, and $\left\|\mathbf {q} \right\|$ is the norm of vector q.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] As all vectors under consideration by this model are element-wise nonnegative, a cosine value of zero means that the query and document vector are orthogonal and have no match (i.e. the query term does not exist in the document being considered).
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] See cosine similarity for further information.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] In the classic vector space model proposed by Salton, Wong and Yang, the term-specific weights in the document vectors are products of local and global parameters.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] The model is known as term frequency–inverse document frequency (tf–idf) model.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Most of these advantages are a consequence of the difference in the density of the document collection representation between Boolean and term frequency-inverse document frequency approaches.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] When using Boolean weights, any document lies in a vertex in a n-dimensional hypercube.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Therefore, the possible document representations are $2^{n}$ and the maximum Euclidean distance between pairs is ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] As documents are added to the document collection, the region defined by the hypercube's vertices become more populated and hence denser.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Unlike Boolean, when a document is added using term frequency-inverse document frequency weights, the inverse document frequencies of the terms in the new document decrease while that of the remaining terms increase.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] In average, as documents are added, the region where documents lie expands regulating the density of the entire collection representation.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] This behavior models the original motivation of Salton and his colleagues that a document collection represented in a low density region could yield better retrieval results.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Many of these difficulties can, however, be overcome by the integration of various tools, including mathematical techniques such as singular value decomposition and lexical databases such as WordNet.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] The following software packages may be of interest to those wishing to experiment with vector models and implement search services based upon them.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] The **Generalized vector space model** is a generalization of the VSM used in information retrieval.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Wong *et al.* presented an analysis of the problems that the pairwise orthogonality assumption of the VSM creates.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] From here they extended the VSM to the generalized vector space model (GVSM).
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Recently Tsatsaronis focused on the first approach.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] They measure semantic relatedness (*SR*) using a thesaurus (*O*) like WordNet.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] It considers the path length, captured by compactness (*SCM*), and the path depth, captured by semantic path elaboration (*SPE*).
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Building also on the first approach, Waitelonis et al. have computed semantic relatedness from Linked Open Data resources including DBpedia as well as the YAGO taxonomy.
[src:topic-modeling/vector-space-model] Thereby they exploits taxonomic relationships among semantic entities in documents and queries after named entity linking.
